# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: shadow-mapping
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] In 3D computer graphics and computer vision, a **depth map** is an image or image channel that contains information relating to the distance of the surfaces of scene objects from a viewpoint.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] The term is related (and may be analogous) to *depth buffer*, *Z-buffer*, *Z-buffering*, and *Z-depth*.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] The "Z" in these latter terms relates to a convention that the central axis of view of a camera is in the direction of the camera's Z axis, and not to the absolute Z axis of a scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] Two different depth maps can be seen here, together with the original model from which they are derived.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] The first depth map shows luminance in proportion to the distance from the camera.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] Nearer surfaces are darker; further surfaces are lighter.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] The second depth map shows luminance in relation to the distances from a nominal focal plane.
[src:shadow-mapping/depth-map] Surfaces closer to the focal plane are darker; surfaces further from the focal plane are lighter, (both closer to and also further away from the viewpoint).
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] In computer graphics, a **shader** is a programmable operation which is applied to data as it moves through the rendering pipeline.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Shaders act on data such as vertices and primitives, generate or morph geometries and fragments, and calculate the colors in a rendered image.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Shaders can execute a wide variety of operations.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] In modern real-time computer graphics, shaders are run on graphics processing units (GPUs) - dedicated hardware which provide parallel execution of programs.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Because image rendering is an embarrassingly parallel problem (having an Amdahl's index of one), shaders benefit greatly from parallel computing, such as SIMD hardware.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The drive for faster rendering has produced highly parallel processors, like GPUs, which are now used for general-purpose computing.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Shaders used for general purposes are commonly called *compute shaders*.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The term "shader" was first introduced to the public by Pixar with version 3.0 of their RenderMan Interface Specification, originally published in May 1988.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] As graphics processing units evolved, major graphics software libraries such as OpenGL and Direct3D began to support shaders.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The first shader-capable GPUs only supported pixel shading, but vertex shaders were quickly introduced once developers realized the power of shaders.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The first video card with a programmable pixel shader was the Nvidia GeForce 3 (NV20), released in 2001.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced with Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Graphics hardware evolved toward a unified shader model, making all shaders equal.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The traditional use of shaders is to operate on data in the graphics pipeline to control the rendering of an image.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Graphics shaders are classified according to their position in the pipeline, the data being manipulated, and the graphics API being used.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Vertex shaders are run once for each 3D vertex given to the graphics processor.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The purpose is to transform each vertex's 3D position in virtual space to the 2D coordinate at which it appears on the screen (as well as a depth value for the Z-buffer).
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Vertex shaders can manipulate properties such as position, color and texture coordinates, but cannot create new vertices.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The output of the vertex shader goes to the next stage in the pipeline, which is either a geometry shader if present, or the rasterizer.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Vertex shaders can enable powerful control over the details of position, movement, lighting, and color in any scene involving 3D models.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Geometry shaders were introduced in Direct3D 10 and OpenGL 3.2; formerly available in OpenGL 2.0+ with the use of extensions.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] This type of shader can generate new graphics primitives, such as points, lines, and triangles, from those primitives that were sent to the beginning of the graphics pipeline.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Geometry shader programs are executed after vertex shaders.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] They take as input a whole primitive, possibly with adjacency information.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] For example, when operating on triangles, the three vertices are the geometry shader's input.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The shader can then emit zero or more primitives, which are rasterized and their fragments ultimately passed to a pixel shader.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Typical uses of a geometry shader include point sprite generation, geometry tessellation, shadow volume extrusion, and single pass rendering to a cube map.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] A typical real-world example of the benefits of geometry shaders would be automatic mesh complexity modification.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] A series of line strips representing control points for a curve are passed to the geometry shader and depending on the complexity required the shader can automatically generate extra lines each of which provides a better approximation of a curve.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] model rendered using fragment shaders with different outputs: solid white, applied texture, physically based shading.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Fragment shaders, also known as **pixel shaders**, compute color and other attributes of each "fragment": a unit of rendering work affecting at most a single output pixel.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The simplest kinds of pixel shaders output one screen pixel as a color value; more complex shaders with multiple inputs/outputs are also possible.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Pixel shaders range from simply always outputting the same color, to applying a lighting value, to doing bump mapping, shadows, specular highlights, translucency and other phenomena.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] They can alter the depth of the fragment (for Z-buffering), or output more than one color if multiple render targets are active.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] In 3D graphics, a pixel shader alone cannot produce some kinds of complex effects because it operates only on a single fragment, without knowledge of a scene's geometry (i.e. vertex data).
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] However, pixel shaders do have knowledge of the screen coordinate being drawn, and can sample the screen and nearby pixels if the contents of the entire screen are passed as a texture to the shader.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] This technique can enable a wide variety of two-dimensional postprocessing effects such as blur, or edge detection/enhancement for cartoon/cel shaders.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Pixel shaders may also be applied in *intermediate* stages to any two-dimensional images—sprites or textures—in the pipeline, whereas vertex shaders always require a 3D scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] For instance, a pixel shader is the only kind of shader that can act as a postprocessor or filter for a video stream after it has been rasterized.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] OpenGL 4.0 and Direct3D 11 introduced a new shader class called a tessellation shader.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The function can be related to a variety of variables, most notably the distance from the viewing camera to allow active level-of-detail scaling.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] This allows objects close to the camera to have fine detail, while further away ones can have more coarse meshes, yet seem comparable in quality.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] It also can drastically reduce required mesh bandwidth by allowing meshes to be refined once inside the shader units instead of down-sampling very complex ones from memory.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Some algorithms can up-sample any arbitrary mesh, while others allow for "hinting" in meshes to dictate the most characteristic vertices and edges.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Circa 2017, the AMD Vega microarchitecture added support for a new shader stage—primitive shaders—somewhat akin to compute shaders with access to the data necessary to process geometry.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Nvidia introduced mesh and task shaders with its Turing microarchitecture in 2018 which are also modelled after compute shaders.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Nvidia Turing is the world's first GPU microarchitecture that supports mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate API, several months before Ampere RTX 30 series was released.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] In 2020, AMD and Nvidia released RDNA 2 and Ampere microarchitectures which both support mesh shading through DirectX 12 Ultimate.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] These mesh shaders allow the GPU to handle more complex algorithms, offloading more work from the CPU to the GPU, and in algorithm intense rendering, increasing the frame rate of or number of triangles in a scene by an order of magnitude.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Intel announced that Intel Arc Alchemist GPUs shipping in Q1 2022 will support mesh shaders.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Ray tracing shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectX Raytracing, by Khronos Group via Vulkan, GLSL, and SPIR-V, by Apple via Metal.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "ray tracing cores".
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Compute kernels are routines compiled for high throughput accelerators (such as graphics processing units (GPUs), digital signal processors (DSPs), or field-programmable gate arrays (FPGAs)), separate from but used by a main program (typically running on a central processing unit).
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] They may be specified by a separate programming language such as "OpenCL C", as "compute shaders" written in a shading language, or embedded directly in application code written in a high level language.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Compute kernels roughly correspond to inner loops when implementing algorithms in traditional languages (except there is no implied sequential operation), or to code passed to internal iterators.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Microsoft support this as DirectCompute.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] This single program, multiple data programming paradigm maps well to vector processors: there is an assumption that each invocation of a kernel within a batch is independent, allowing for data parallel execution.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] However, atomic operations may sometimes be used for synchronization between elements (for interdependent work), in some scenarios.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Individual invocations are given indices (in 1 or more dimensions) from which arbitrary addressing of buffer data may be performed (including scatter gather operations), so long as the non-overlapping assumption is respected.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The Vulkan API provides the intermediate SPIR-V representation to describe *both* graphical shaders, and compute kernels in a language independent and machine independent manner.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The intention is to facilitate language evolution and provide a more natural ability to leverage GPU compute capabilities, in line with hardware developments such as Unified Memory Architecture and Heterogeneous System Architecture.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] This allows closer cooperation between a CPU and GPU.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Much work has been done in the field of Kernel generation through LLMs as a means of optimizing code.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] KernelBench, created by the Scaling Intelligence Lab at Stanford, provides a framework to evaluate the ability of LLMs to generate efficient GPU kernels.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Cognition has created Kevin 32-B to create efficient CUDA kernels which is currently the highest performing model on KernelBench.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Tensor shaders are accelerator programs that deal with matrix operations on large arrays, a type of operation commonly used in neural network-based AI.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Tensor shaders are supported by Microsoft via DirectML, by Khronos Group via OpenVX, by Apple via Core ML, by Google via TensorFlow, by Linux Foundation via ONNX.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Nvidia and AMD called the parts of the hardware responsible for executing these shaders "tensor cores".
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Several programming languages exist specifically for writing shaders, and which is used can depend on the target environment.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The shading language for OpenGL is GLSL, and Direct3D uses HLSL.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The Metal framework, used by Apple devices, has its own shading language called Metal Shading Language.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Increasingly in modern graphics APIs, shaders are compiled into SPIR-V, an intermediate language, before they are distributed to the end user.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] This standard allows more flexible choice of shading language, regardless of target platform.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] First supported by Vulkan and OpenGL, SPIR-V is also being adopted by Direct3D.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] The graph is then compiled into a shader.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] In web development contexts, visual and component-based shader tools have also emerged.
[src:shadow-mapping/pixel-shader] Platforms such as shaders.com provide component-driven composition of shaders for integration into frontend frameworks including Vue, React, and Svelte, while tools such as Shadertoy and FragCoord.xyz focus on lower-level shader authoring and debugging.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In a computer graphics context, in standard usage, the word "rendering" by itself means rendering 3D scenes, but it is sometimes used with a broader meaning.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A modifier such as "2D" or "3D" is used when there is potential ambiguity (e.g.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A software application or component that performs rendering is called a **rendering engine**, **render engine**, **rendering system**, **graphics engine**, or simply a **renderer**.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A distinction is made between real-time rendering, in which images are generated and displayed immediately (ideally fast enough to give the impression of motion or animation), and offline rendering (sometimes called pre-rendering) in which images or film frames, are generated for later viewing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Offline rendering can use a slower and higher-quality renderer.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Interactive applications such as games must primarily use real-time rendering, although they may incorporate pre-rendered content.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering produces images of scenes or objects defined using coordinates in 3D space, seen from a particular viewpoint.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It uses knowledge and ideas from optics, the study of visual perception, mathematics, and software engineering, and it has applications such as video games, simulators, visual effects for films and television, design visualization, and medical diagnosis.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering requires modeling the propagation of light in an environment, e.g. by applying the rendering equation.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Real-time rendering uses high-performance *rasterization* algorithms that process a list of shapes and determine which pixels are covered by each shape.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When more realism is required (e.g. for architectural visualization or visual effects) slower pixel-by-pixel algorithms such as *ray tracing* are used instead.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (Ray tracing can also be used selectively during rasterized rendering to improve the realism of lighting and reflections.) A type of ray tracing called *path tracing* is currently the most common technique for photorealistic rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Path tracing is also popular for generating high-quality non-photorealistic images, such as frames for 3D animated films.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Both rasterization and ray tracing can be sped up ("accelerated") by specially designed microprocessors called GPUs.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rasterization algorithms are also used to produce images containing only 2D shapes such as polygons and text.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] This type of rendering is sometimes called *2D rendering*, and its applications include digital illustration, graphic design, 2D animation, desktop publishing and the display of user interfaces.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, rendering was called **image synthesis** but today this term is likely to mean AI image generation.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The term "neural rendering" is sometimes used when a neural network is the primary means of generating an image but some degree of control over the output image is provided.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks can also assist rendering without replacing traditional algorithms, e.g. by removing noise from path traced images.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A large proportion of computer graphics research has worked towards producing images that resemble photographs.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Fundamental techniques that make this possible were invented in the 1980s, but at the end of the decade, photorealism for complex scenes was still considered a distant goal.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Today, photorealism is routinely achievable for offline rendering, but remains difficult for real-time rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In order to produce realistic images, rendering must simulate how light travels from light sources, is reflected, refracted, and scattered (often many times) by objects in the scene, passes through a camera lens, and finally reaches the film or sensor of the camera.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The physics used in these simulations is primarily geometrical optics, in which particles of light follow (usually straight) lines called *rays*, but in some situations (such as when rendering thin films, like the surface of soap bubbles) the wave nature of light must be taken into account.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In realistic scenes, objects are illuminated both by light that arrives directly from a light source (after passing mostly unimpeded through air), and light that has bounced off other objects in the scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The simulation of this complex lighting is called global illumination.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In the past, indirect lighting was often faked (especially when rendering animated films) by placing additional hidden lights in the scene, but today path tracing is used to render it accurately.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For true photorealism, the camera used to take the photograph must be simulated.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The *thin lens approximation* allows combining perspective projection with depth of field (and bokeh) emulation.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Camera lens simulations can be made more realistic by modeling the way light is refracted by the components of the lens.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Motion blur is often simulated if film or video frames are being rendered.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Simulated lens flare and bloom are sometimes added to make the image appear subjectively brighter (although the design of real cameras tries to reduce these effects).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Realistic rendering uses mathematical descriptions of how different surface materials reflect light, called *reflectance models* or (when physically plausible) *bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs)*.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Rendering materials such as marble, plant leaves, and human skin requires simulating an effect called subsurface scattering, in which a portion of the light travels into the material, is scattered, and then travels back out again.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The way color, and properties such as roughness, vary over a surface can be represented efficiently using texture mapping.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] For some applications (including early stages of 3D modeling), simplified rendering styles such as wireframe rendering may be appropriate, particularly when the material and surface details have not been defined and only the shape of an object is known.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Games and other real-time applications may use simpler and less realistic rendering techniques as an artistic or design choice, or to allow higher frame rates on lower-end hardware.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Orthographic and isometric projections can be used for a stylized effect or to ensure that parallel lines are depicted as parallel in CAD rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Non-photorealistic rendering (NPR) uses techniques like edge detection and posterization to produce 3D images that resemble technical illustrations, cartoons, or other styles of drawing or painting.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In 2D computer graphics the positions and sizes of shapes are specified using 2D coordinates (x and y) instead of 3D coordinates (x, y, and z).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering APIs often use a resolution-independent coordinate system, with a viewport determining how to convert coordinates to pixel indexes called *device coordinates*.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transformations such as scaling, translation, and rotation may be applied before rendering the shapes.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These affine transformations are often represented by 3 × 3 matrices, allowing easier composition of transformations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Higher-quality 2D rendering engines such as SVG renderers usually implement anti-aliasing to reduce the jagged appearance of rasterized lines and shape edges.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering overlapping shapes, renderers commonly use a "painter's model" in which the shapes are drawn in some determined order, or their contributions to each pixel are composited using blending operations that may depend on the order of the inputs.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers may allow giving shapes a "z index" or "stacking order" to specify the rendering or blending order (unlike the z coordinate used in 3D rendering, this third coordinate only indicates an order, not a distance, and cannot be meaningfully rotated together with the x and y coordinates).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering typically does not simulate light propagation (which would likely require specifying 3D positions or thickness for the shapes).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Effects such as drop shadows and transparency are defined by mathematical functions with no physical basis.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 2D rendering for print output may need to support very high resolutions, e.g.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] 600 or 1200 DPI for a typical laser printer, or 2400 DPI or higher for an imagesetter or platesetter.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Grayscale and color images require halftones (or some form of dithering or stochastic screening) and color separations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A rendering engine called a *raster image processor* (RIP) converts input data such as PDF files into the high-resolution bitmap images used by the printer.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before a 3D scene or 2D image can be rendered, it must be described in a way that the rendering software can understand.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Historically, inputs for both 2D and 3D rendering were usually text files, which are easier than binary files for humans to edit and debug.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Traditional rendering algorithms use geometric descriptions of 3D scenes or 2D images.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Applications and algorithms that render visualizations of data scanned from the real world, or scientific simulations, may require different types of input data.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The PostScript format (which is often credited with the rise of desktop publishing) provides a standardized, interoperable way to describe 2D graphics and page layout.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The Scalable Vector Graphics (SVG) format is also text-based, and the PDF format uses the PostScript language internally.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Many file formats exist for storing individual 3D objects or "models".
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These can be imported into a larger scene, or loaded on-demand by rendering software or games.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A realistic scene may require hundreds of items like household objects, vehicles, and trees, and 3D artists often utilize large libraries of models.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] In game production, these models (along with other data such as textures, audio files, and animations) are referred to as "assets".
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scientific and engineering visualization often requires rendering volumetric data generated by 3D scans or simulations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Perhaps the most common source of such data is medical CT and MRI scans, which need to be rendered for diagnosis.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Volumetric data can be extremely large, and requires specialized data formats to store it efficiently, particularly if the volume is *sparse* (with empty regions that do not contain data).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Before rendering, level sets for volumetric data can be extracted and converted into a mesh of triangles, e.g. by using the marching cubes algorithm.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms have also been developed that work directly with volumetric data, for example to render realistic depictions of the way light is scattered and absorbed by clouds and smoke, and this type of volumetric rendering is used extensively in visual effects for movies.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] When rendering lower-resolution volumetric data without interpolation, the individual cubes or "voxels" may be visible, an effect sometimes used deliberately for game graphics.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photographs of real world objects can be incorporated into a rendered scene by using them as textures for 3D objects.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Photos of a scene can also be stitched together to create panoramic images or environment maps, which allow the scene to be rendered very efficiently but only from a single viewpoint.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Scanning of real objects and scenes using structured light or lidar produces point clouds consisting of the coordinates of millions of individual points in space, sometimes along with color information.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] These point clouds may either be rendered directly or converted into meshes before rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] A more recent, experimental approach is description of scenes using radiance fields which define the color, intensity, and direction of incoming light at each point in space.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] (This is conceptually similar to, but not identical to, the light field recorded by a hologram.) For any useful resolution, the amount of data in a radiance field is so large that it is impractical to represent it directly as volumetric data, and an approximation function must be found.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Neural networks are typically used to generate and evaluate these approximations, sometimes using video frames, or a collection of photographs of a scene taken at different angles, as "training data".
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Algorithms related to neural networks have recently been used to find approximations of a scene as 3D Gaussians.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The resulting representation is similar to a point cloud, except that it uses fuzzy, partially-transparent blobs of varying dimensions and orientations instead of points.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] As with neural radiance fields, these approximations are often generated from photographs or video frames.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of rendering may be displayed immediately on the screen (many times a second, in the case of real-time rendering such as games) or saved in a raster graphics file format such as JPEG or PNG.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] High-end rendering applications commonly use the OpenEXR file format, which can represent finer gradations of colors and high dynamic range lighting, allowing tone mapping or other adjustments to be applied afterwards without loss of quality.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The output of a renderer sometimes includes more than just RGB color values.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Transparency information can be included, allowing rendered foreground objects to be composited with photographs or video.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] It is also sometimes useful to store the contributions of different lights, or of specular and diffuse lighting, as separate channels, so lighting can be adjusted after rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] The OpenEXR format allows storing many channels of data in a single file.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p01] Renderers such as Blender and Pixar RenderMan support a large variety of configurable values called Arbitrary Output Variables (AOVs).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Choosing how to render a 3D scene usually involves trade-offs between speed, memory usage, and realism (although realism is not always desired).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The **algorithms** developed over the years follow a loose progression, with more advanced methods becoming practical as computing power and memory capacity increased.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Multiple techniques may be used for a single final image.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important distinction is between image order algorithms, which iterate over pixels in the image, and object order algorithms, which iterate over objects in the scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For simple scenes, object order is usually more efficient, as there are fewer objects than pixels.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] algorithms that also support filled shapes.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In principle, any 2D vector graphics renderer can be used to render 3D objects by first projecting them onto a 2D image plane.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Different realistic or stylized effects can be obtained by coloring the pixels covered by the objects in different ways.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization is usually synonymous with "object order" rendering (as described above).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It can be used to implement "image order" rendering by casting a ray for each pixel, and finding a corresponding point in the scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , requiring a varying number of ray casting operations for each path.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] is usually in the domain of path tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] approach that breaks surfaces in the scene into pieces, and estimates the amount of light that each piece receives from light sources, or indirectly from other surfaces.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] of each surface is known, the scene can be rendered using rasterization or ray tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] , giving ray tracing a rigorous mathematical foundation.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Each of the above approaches has many variations, and there is some overlap.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing may be considered either a distinct technique or a particular type of ray tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that the usage of terminology related to ray tracing and path tracing has changed significantly over time.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray marching is a family of algorithms, used by ray casting, for finding intersections between a ray and a complex object, such as a volumetric dataset or a surface defined by a signed distance function.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It is not, by itself, a rendering method, but it can be incorporated into ray tracing and path tracing, and is used by rasterization to implement screen-space reflection and other effects.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A technique called photon mapping traces paths of photons from a light source to an object, accumulating data about irradiance which is then used during conventional ray tracing or path tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering a scene using only rays traced from the light source to the camera is impractical, even though it corresponds more closely to reality, because a huge number of photons would need to be simulated, only a tiny fraction of which actually hit the camera.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Some authors call conventional ray tracing "backward" ray tracing because it traces the paths of photons backwards from the camera to the light source, and call following paths from the light source (as in photon mapping) "forward" ray tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, sometimes the meaning of these terms is reversed.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Tracing rays starting at the light source can also be called *particle tracing* or *light tracing*, which avoids this ambiguity.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real-time rendering, including video game graphics, typically uses rasterization, but increasingly combines it with ray tracing and path tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To enable realistic global illumination, real-time rendering often relies on pre-rendered ("baked") lighting for stationary objects.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For moving objects, it may use a technique called *light probes*, in which lighting is recorded by rendering omnidirectional views of the scene at chosen points in space (often points on a grid to allow easier interpolation).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These are similar to environment maps, but typically use a very low resolution or an approximation such as spherical harmonics.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The term *rasterization* (in a broad sense) encompasses many techniques used for 2D rendering and real-time 3D rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] 3D animated films were rendered by rasterization before ray tracing and path tracing became practical.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A renderer combines rasterization with *geometry processing* (which is not specific to rasterization) and *pixel processing* which computes the RGB color values to be placed in the *framebuffer* for display.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, 3D rasterization used algorithms like the *Warnock algorithm* and *scanline rendering* (also called "scan-conversion"), which can handle arbitrary polygons and can rasterize many shapes simultaneously.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Although such algorithms are still important for 2D rendering, 3D rendering now usually divides shapes into triangles and rasterizes them individually using simpler methods.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] High-performance algorithms exist for rasterizing 2D lines, including anti-aliased lines, as well as ellipses and filled triangles.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important special case of 2D rasterization is text rendering, which requires careful anti-aliasing and rounding of coordinates to avoid distorting the letterforms and preserve spacing, density, and sharpness.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After 3D coordinates have been projected onto the image plane, rasterization is primarily a 2D problem, but the 3rd dimension necessitates *hidden surface removal*.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early computer graphics used geometric algorithms or ray casting to remove the hidden portions of shapes, or used the *painter's algorithm*, which sorts shapes by depth (distance from camera) and renders them from back to front.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Depth sorting was later avoided by incorporating depth comparison into the scanline rendering algorithm.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The *z-buffer* algorithm performs the comparisons indirectly by including a depth or "z" value in the framebuffer.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A pixel is only covered by a shape if that shape's z value is lower (indicating closer to the camera) than the z value currently in the buffer.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The z-buffer requires additional memory (an expensive resource at the time it was invented) but simplifies the rasterization code and permits multiple passes.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Memory is now faster and more plentiful, and a z-buffer is almost always used for real-time rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A drawback of the basic z-buffer algorithm is that each pixel ends up either entirely covered by a single object or filled with the background color, causing jagged edges in the final image.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early *anti-aliasing* approaches addressed this by detecting when a pixel is partially covered by a shape, and calculating the covered area.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The A-buffer (and other supersampling and multi-sampling techniques) solve the problem less precisely but with higher performance.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time 3D graphics, it has become common to use complicated heuristics (and even neural-networks) to perform anti-aliasing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In 3D rasterization, color is usually determined by a *pixel shader* or *fragment shader*, a small program that is run for each pixel.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Until relatively recently, Pixar used rasterization for rendering its animated films.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Unlike the renderers commonly used for real-time graphics, the Reyes rendering system in Pixar's RenderMan software was optimized for rendering very small (pixel-sized) polygons, and incorporated stochastic sampling techniques more typically associated with ray tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the simplest ways to render a 3D scene is to test if a ray starting at the viewpoint (the "eye" or "camera") intersects any of the geometric shapes in the scene, repeating this test using a different ray direction for each pixel.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This method, called *ray casting*, was important in early computer graphics, and is a fundamental building block for more advanced algorithms.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render shapes defined by *constructive solid geometry* (CSG) operations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Early ray casting experiments include the work of Arthur Appel in the 1960s.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Appel rendered shadows by casting an additional ray from each visible surface point towards a light source.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] He also tried rendering the density of illumination by casting random rays from the light source towards the object and plotting the intersection points (similar to the later technique called *photon mapping*).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When rendering scenes containing many objects, testing the intersection of a ray with every object becomes very expensive.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Special data structures are used to speed up this process by allowing large numbers of objects to be excluded quickly (such as objects behind the camera).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These structures are analogous to database indexes for finding the relevant objects.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The most common are the *bounding volume hierarchy* (BVH), which stores a pre-computed bounding box or sphere for each branch of a tree of objects, and the *k-d tree* which recursively divides space into two parts.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs include hardware acceleration for BVH intersection tests.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] K-d trees are a special case of *binary space partitioning*, which was frequently used in early computer graphics (it can also generate a rasterization order for the painter's algorithm).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Octrees*, another historically popular technique, are still often used for volumetric data.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Geometric formulas are sufficient for finding the intersection of a ray with shapes like spheres, polygons, and polyhedra, but for most curved surfaces there is no analytic solution, or the intersection is difficult to compute accurately using limited precision floating point numbers.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Root-finding algorithms such as Newton's method can sometimes be used.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] To avoid these complications, curved surfaces are often approximated as meshes of triangles.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Volume rendering (e.g. rendering clouds and smoke), and some surfaces such as fractals, may require ray marching instead of basic ray casting.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray casting can be used to render an image by tracing light rays backwards from a simulated camera.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] After finding a point on a surface where a ray originated, another ray is traced towards the light source to determine if anything is casting a shadow on that point.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If there are multiple light sources, brightness contributions of the lights are added together.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For color images, calculations are repeated for multiple wavelengths of light (e.g. red, green, and blue).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing usually performs anti-aliasing by taking the average of multiple samples for each pixel.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It may also use multiple samples for effects like depth of field and motion blur.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If evenly spaced ray directions or times are used for each of these features, many rays are required, and some aliasing will remain.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Cook-style*, *stochastic*, or *Monte Carlo ray tracing* avoids this problem by using random sampling instead of evenly spaced samples.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of ray tracing is commonly called *distributed ray tracing*, or *distribution ray tracing* because it samples rays from probability distributions.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Distribution ray tracing can also render realistic "soft" shadows from large lights by using a random sample of points on the light when testing for shadowing, and it can simulate chromatic aberration by sampling multiple wavelengths from the spectrum of light.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Real surface materials reflect small amounts of light in almost every direction because they have small (or microscopic) bumps and grooves.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A distribution ray tracer can simulate this by sampling possible ray directions, which allows rendering blurry reflections from glossy and metallic surfaces.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However, if this procedure is repeated recursively to simulate realistic indirect lighting, and if more than one sample is taken at each surface point, the tree of rays quickly becomes huge.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Another kind of ray tracing, called *path tracing*, handles indirect light more efficiently, avoiding branching, and ensures that the distribution of all possible paths from a light source to the camera is sampled in an unbiased way.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing was often used for rendering reflections in animated films, until path tracing became standard for film rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Films such as Shrek 2 and Monsters University also used distribution ray tracing or path tracing to precompute indirect illumination for a scene or frame prior to rendering it using rasterization.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advances in GPU technology have made real-time ray tracing possible in games, although it is currently almost always used in combination with rasterization.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This enables visual effects that are difficult with only rasterization, including reflection from curved surfaces and interreflective objects, and shadows that are accurate over a wide range of distances and surface orientations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing support is included in recent versions of the graphics APIs used by games, such as DirectX, Metal, and Vulkan.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Ray tracing has been used to render simulated black holes, and the appearance of objects moving at close to the speed of light, by taking spacetime curvature and relativistic effects into account during light ray simulation.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity (named after the radiometric quantity of the same name) is a method for rendering objects illuminated by light bouncing off rough or matte surfaces.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This type of illumination is called *indirect light*, *environment lighting*, *diffuse lighting*, or *diffuse interreflection*, and the problem of rendering it realistically is called *global illumination*.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rasterization and basic forms of ray tracing (other than distribution ray tracing and path tracing) can only roughly approximate indirect light, e.g. by adding a uniform "ambient" lighting amount chosen by the artist.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Radiosity techniques are also suited to rendering scenes with *area lights* such as rectangular fluorescent lighting panels, which are difficult for rasterization and traditional ray tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the original radiosity method (first proposed in 1984) now called *classical radiosity*, surfaces and lights in the scene are split into pieces called *patches*, a process called *meshing* (this step makes it a finite element method).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The rendering code must then determine what fraction of the light being emitted or diffusely reflected (scattered) by each patch is received by each other patch.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] These fractions are called *form factors* or *view factors* (first used in engineering to model radiative heat transfer).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The form factors are multiplied by the albedo of the receiving surface and put in a matrix.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The lighting in the scene can then be expressed as a matrix equation (or equivalently a system of linear equations) that can be solved by methods from linear algebra.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Solving the radiosity equation gives the total amount of light emitted and reflected by each patch, which is divided by area to get a value called *radiosity* that can be used when rasterizing or ray tracing to determine the color of pixels corresponding to visible parts of the patch.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For real-time rendering, this value (or more commonly the irradiance, which does not depend on local surface albedo) can be pre-computed and stored in a texture (called an *irradiance map*) or stored as vertex data for 3D models.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This feature was used in architectural visualization software to allow real-time walk-throughs of a building interior after computing the lighting.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The large size of the matrices used in classical radiosity (the square of the number of patches) causes problems for realistic scenes.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Practical implementations may use Jacobi or Gauss-Seidel iterations, which is equivalent (at least in the Jacobi case) to simulating the propagation of light one bounce at a time until the amount of light remaining (not yet absorbed by surfaces) is insignificant.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Form factors may be recomputed when they are needed, to avoid storing a complete matrix in memory.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The quality of rendering is often determined by the size of the patches, e.g. very fine meshes are needed to depict the edges of shadows accurately.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] An important improvement is *hierarchical radiosity*, which uses a coarser mesh (larger patches) for simulating the transfer of light between surfaces that are far away from one another, and adaptively sub-divides the patches as needed.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This allows radiosity to be used for much larger and more complex scenes.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Alternative and extended versions of the radiosity method support non-Lambertian surfaces, such as glossy surfaces and mirrors, and sometimes use volumes or "clusters" of objects as well as surface patches.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Simplified and partially precomputed versions of radiosity are widely used for real-time rendering, combined with techniques such as *octree radiosity* that store approximations of the light field.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As part of the approach known as *physically based rendering*, **path tracing** has become the dominant technique for rendering realistic scenes, including effects for movies.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For example, the popular open source 3D software Blender uses path tracing in its Cycles renderer.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Like *distributed ray tracing*, path tracing is a kind of *stochastic* or *randomized* ray tracing that uses Monte Carlo or Quasi-Monte Carlo integration.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was proposed and named in 1986 by Jim Kajiya in the same paper as the rendering equation.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Kajiya suggested reducing the noise present in the output images by using *stratified sampling* and *importance sampling* for making random decisions such as choosing which ray to follow at each step of a path.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Even with these techniques, path tracing would not have been practical for film rendering, using computers available at the time, because the computational cost of generating enough samples to reduce variance to an acceptable level was too high.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Monster House, the first feature film rendered entirely using path tracing, was not released until 20 years later.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In its basic form, path tracing is inefficient (requiring too many samples) for rendering caustics and scenes where light enters indirectly through narrow spaces.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Attempts were made to address these weaknesses in the 1990s.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Metropolis light transport* samples paths by modifying paths that were previously traced, spending more time exploring paths that are similar to other "bright" paths, which increases the chance of discovering even brighter paths.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] *Multiple importance sampling* provides a way to reduce variance when combining samples from more than one sampling method, particularly when some samples are much noisier than the others.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] This later work was summarized and expanded upon in Eric Veach's 1997 PhD thesis, which helped raise interest in path tracing in the computer graphics community.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The Arnold renderer, first released in 1998, proved that path tracing was practical for rendering frames for films, and that there was a demand for unbiased and physically based rendering in the film industry; other commercial and open source path tracing renderers began appearing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Computational cost was addressed by rapid advances in CPU and cluster performance.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Path tracing's relative simplicity and its nature as a Monte Carlo method (sampling hundreds or thousands of paths per pixel) have made it attractive to implement on a GPU, especially on recent GPUs that support ray tracing acceleration technology such as Nvidia's RTX and OptiX.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] However bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport are more difficult to implement efficiently on a GPU.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Techniques have been developed to denoise the output of path tracing, reducing the number of paths required to achieve acceptable quality, at the risk of losing some detail or introducing small-scale artifacts that are more objectionable than noise.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks are now widely used for this purpose.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Research into improving path tracing continues.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Many variations of bidirectional path tracing and Metropolis light transport have been explored, and ways of combining path tracing with photon mapping.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent *path guiding* approaches construct approximations of the light field probability distribution in each volume of space, so paths can be sampled more effectively.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] By combining denoising and hardware ray tracing acceleration, it is now practical to use path tracing for real-time rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to performance constraints, biased techniques such as a radiance cache may be incorporated.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Spatiotemporal reservoir resampling (ReSTIR) aims to improve the quality of real-time path tracing and allow more complex lighting by reusing samples (paths) from previous frames and adjacent pixels.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As of 2003, machine learning (ML) techniques were being used in other areas of computer graphics, such as texture synthesis, fitting surfaces to point clouds, and fitting curves to motion capture data.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The use of ML for rendering expanded with the availability of GPUs that can evaluate neural networks (especially convolutional neural networks) quickly.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural networks and Gaussian mixture models have been used in conjunction with rendering techniques such as path tracing to encode bidirectional reflectance distribution functions (BRDFs), or to encode cached radiance at points in space (for biased acceleration of rendering or for path guiding).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Neural radiance fields (NeRFs) take the latter approach to an extreme, encoding radiance at all points in a volume, and using evaluation of this approximation as the primary rendering method.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] One of the most widely used applications of machine learning in rendering is denoising of path traced images (in practice, most path tracing now likely uses such a denoiser).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Denoisers specialized for real-time rendering can work with very low sample counts and improve temporal coherence to reduce flickering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering is usually limited by available computing power and memory bandwidth, and so specialized hardware has been developed to speed it up ("accelerate" it), particularly for real-time rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware features such as a framebuffer for raster graphics are required to display the output of rendering smoothly in real time.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Hardware acceleration does not replace the use of software for rendering, rather it speeds up selected operations or calculations using dedicated circuits, or runs portions of the software's code on a different type of processor.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In the era of vector monitors (also called *calligraphic displays*), a display processing unit (DPU) was a dedicated CPU or coprocessor that maintained a list of visual elements and redrew them continuously on the screen by controlling an electron beam.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Advanced DPUs such as Evans & Sutherland's Line Drawing System-1 (and later models produced into the 1980s) incorporated 3D coordinate transformation features to accelerate rendering of wire-frame images.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Evans & Sutherland also made the Digistar planetarium projection system, which was a vector display that could render both stars and wire-frame graphics (the vector-based Digistar and Digistar II were used in many planetariums, and a few may still be in operation).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] A Digistar prototype was used for rendering 3D star fields for the film Star Trek II: The Wrath of Khan – some of the first 3D computer graphics sequences ever seen in a feature film.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Shaded 3D graphics rendering in the 1970s and early 1980s was usually implemented on general-purpose computers, such as the PDP-10 used by researchers at the University of Utah.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] It was difficult to speed up using specialized hardware because it involves a pipeline of complex steps, requiring data addressing, decision-making, and computation capabilities typically only provided by CPUs (although dedicated circuits for speeding up particular operations were proposed ).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Supercomputers or specially designed multi-CPU computers or clusters were sometimes used for ray tracing.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Clark and Marc Hannah designed the Geometry Engine, a VLSI chip for performing some of the steps of the 3D rasterization pipeline, and started the company Silicon Graphics (SGI) to commercialize this technology.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Home computers and game consoles in the 1980s contained graphics coprocessors that were capable of scrolling and filling areas of the display, and drawing sprites and lines, though they were not useful for rendering realistic images.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Towards the end of the 1980s PC graphics cards and arcade games with 3D rendering acceleration began to appear, and in the 1990s such technology became commonplace.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Today, even low-power mobile processors typically incorporate 3D graphics acceleration features.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The 3D graphics accelerators of the 1990s evolved into modern GPUs.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] GPUs are general-purpose processors, like CPUs, but they are designed for tasks that can be broken into many small, similar, mostly independent sub-tasks (such as rendering individual pixels) and performed in parallel.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Due to their origins, GPUs typically still provide specialized hardware acceleration for some steps of a traditional 3D rasterization pipeline, including hidden surface removal using a z-buffer, and texture mapping with mipmaps, but these features are no longer always used.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Recent GPUs have features to accelerate finding the intersections of rays with a bounding volume hierarchy, to help speed up all variants of ray tracing and path tracing, as well as neural network acceleration features sometimes useful for rendering.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Rendering algorithms will run efficiently on a GPU only if they can be implemented using small groups of threads that perform mostly the same operations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] As an example of code that meets this requirement: when rendering a small square of pixels in a simple ray-traced image, all threads will likely be intersecting rays with the same object and performing the same lighting computations.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] For performance and architectural reasons, GPUs run groups of around 16-64 threads called *warps* or *wavefronts* in lock-step (all threads in the group are executing the same instructions at the same time).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] If not all threads in the group need to run particular blocks of code (due to conditions) then some threads will be idle, or the results of their computations will be discarded, causing degraded performance.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Historically, the term *hardware rendering* (possibly an abbreviation of "hardware accelerated rendering" or "hardware-assisted rendering") was sometimes used to mean rendering using a hardware-accelerated rasterization pipeline (typically for real-time rendering).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] In contrast, *software rendering* meant offline rendering using software that was not limited by the capabilities of graphics hardware, and could use more realistic and higher quality techniques.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Both hardware and software have evolved, and although these terms are still used, their meaning may now be context-dependent.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When OpenGL and Direct3D were introduced in the 1990s, there was a need to use these APIs on computers that did not have hardware acceleration for 3D graphics.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] "Fallback" rendering implementations were provided that did not require special hardware, and these are sometimes called "software renderers" (today hardware acceleration is almost always available, and these CPU-only implementations are used primarily for testing).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] More recently, "software rendering" may also mean rendering that does not use graphics APIs such as OpenGL, Metal, Direct3D, or Vulkan.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Types of renderers that in the past might have been called "software renderers" (e.g. path tracing renderers used for offline rendering for movies) now commonly use GPU acceleration, often via APIs such as CUDA or OpenCL, which are not graphics-specific.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Since these latter APIs allow running C++ code on a GPU, it is now possible to run the same rendering code on either a CPU or GPU.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The following is a rough timeline of frequently mentioned rendering techniques, including areas of current research.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] Note that even in cases where an idea was named in a specific paper, there were almost always multiple researchers or teams working in the same area (including earlier related work).
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] When a method is first proposed it is often very inefficient, and it takes additional research and practical efforts to turn it into a useful technique.
[src:shadow-mapping/rendering-computer-graphics-p02] The list focuses on academic research and does not include hardware.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Shadows are created by testing whether a pixel is visible from the light source, by comparing the pixel to a z-buffer or *depth* image of the light source's view, stored in the form of a texture.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] If you looked out from a source of light, all the objects you can see would appear in light.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Anything behind those objects, however, would be in shadow.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This is the basic principle used to create a shadow map.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The light's view is rendered, storing the depth of every surface it sees (the shadow map).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Next, the regular scene is rendered comparing the depth of every point drawn (as if it were being seen by the light, rather than the eye) to this depth map.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This technique is less accurate than shadow volumes, but the shadow map can be a faster alternative depending on how much fill time is required for either technique in a particular application and therefore may be more suitable to real-time applications.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] In addition, shadow maps do not require the use of an additional stencil buffer and can be modified to produce shadows with a soft edge.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Unlike shadow volumes, however, the accuracy of a shadow map is limited by its resolution.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Rendering a shadowed scene involves two major drawing steps.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The first produces the shadow map itself, and the second applies it to the scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Depending on the implementation (and the number of lights), this may require two or more drawing passes.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The first step renders the scene from the light's point of view.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] For a point light source, the view should be a perspective projection as wide as its desired angle of effect (it will be a sort of square spotlight).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] For directional light (e.g., that from the Sun), an orthographic projection should be used.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] From this rendering, the depth buffer is extracted and saved.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Because only the depth information is relevant, it is common to avoid updating the color buffers and disable all lighting and texture calculations for this rendering, to save drawing time.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This depth map is often stored as a texture in graphics memory.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This depth map must be updated any time there are changes to either the light or the objects in the scene, but can be reused in other situations, such as those where only the viewing camera moves.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] In many implementations, it is practical to render only a subset of the objects in the scene to the shadow map to save some of the time it takes to redraw the map.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Also, a depth offset which shifts the objects away from the light may be applied to the shadow map rendering in an attempt to resolve stitching problems where the depth map value is close to the depth of a surface being drawn (i.e., the shadow-casting surface) in the next step.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Alternatively, culling front faces and only rendering the back of objects to the shadow map is sometimes used for a similar result.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The second step is to draw the scene from the usual camera viewpoint, applying the shadow map.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This process has three major components.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The second step is the depth test which compares the object z values against the z values from the depth map, and finally, once accomplished, the object must be drawn either in shadow or in light.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] To test a point against the depth map, its position in the scene coordinates must be transformed into the equivalent position as seen by the light.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This is accomplished by a matrix multiplication.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The location of the object on the screen is determined by the usual coordinate transformation, but a second set of coordinates must be generated to locate the object in light space.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The matrix used to transform the world coordinates into the light's viewing coordinates is the same as the one used to render the shadow map in the first step (under OpenGL this is the product of the model, view and projection matrices).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This will produce a set of homogeneous coordinates that need a perspective division (*see 3D projection*) to become *normalized device coordinates*, in which each component (*x*, *y*, or *z*) falls between −1 and 1 (if it is visible from the light view).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Many implementations (such as OpenGL and Direct3D) require an additional *scale and bias* matrix multiplication to map those −1 to 1 values to 0 to 1, which are more usual coordinates for depth map (texture map) lookup.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] If done with a shader, or other graphics hardware extension, this transformation is usually applied at the vertex level, and the generated value is interpolated between other vertices and passed to the fragment level.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Once the light-space coordinates are found, the *x* and *y* values usually correspond to a location in the depth map texture, and the *z* value corresponds to its associated depth, which can now be tested against the depth map.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] If the *z* value is greater than the value stored in the depth map at the appropriate (*x*,*y*) location, the object is considered to be behind an occluding object and should be marked as a *failure*, to be drawn in shadow by the drawing process.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] If the (*x*,*y*) location falls outside the depth map, the programmer must either decide that the surface should be lit or shadowed by default (usually lit).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] In a shader implementation, this test would be done at the fragment level.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Also, care needs to be taken when selecting the type of texture map storage to be used by the hardware: if interpolation cannot be done, the shadow will appear to have a sharp, jagged edge (an effect that can be reduced with greater shadow map resolution).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] It is possible to modify the depth map test to produce shadows with a soft edge by using a range of values (based on the proximity to the edge of the shadow) rather than simply pass or fail.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The shadow mapping technique can also be modified to draw a texture onto the lit regions, simulating the effect of a projector.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The picture above captioned "visualization of the depth map projected onto the scene" is an example of such a process.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Drawing the scene with shadows can be done in several different ways.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] If programmable shaders are available, the depth map test may be performed by a fragment shader which simply draws the object in shadow or lighted depending on the result, drawing the scene in a single pass (after an initial earlier pass to generate the shadow map).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Enable the depth map test and render the scene lit.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Areas where the depth map test fails will not be overwritten and will remain shadowed.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] An additional pass may be used for each additional light, using additive blending to combine their effect with the lights already drawn.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] The example pictures in this article used the OpenGL extension *GL_ARB_shadow_ambient* to accomplish the shadow map process in two passes.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] One of the key disadvantages of real-time shadow mapping is that the size and depth of the shadow map determine the quality of the final shadows.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] This is usually visible as aliasing or shadow continuity glitches.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] A simple way to overcome this limitation is to increase the shadow map size, but due to memory, computational or hardware constraints, it is not always possible.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Commonly used techniques for real-time shadow mapping have been developed to circumvent this limitation.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] These include Cascaded Shadow Maps, Trapezoidal Shadow Maps, Light Space Perspective Shadow maps, or Parallel-Split Shadow maps.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Also notable is that generated shadows, even if aliasing free, have hard edges, which is not always desirable.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] In order to emulate real world soft shadows, several solutions have been developed, either by doing several lookups on the shadow map, generating geometry meant to emulate the soft edge or creating non-standard depth shadow maps.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-mapping] Notable examples of these are Percentage Closer Filtering, Smoothies, and Variance Shadow maps.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] The stencil buffer implementation of shadow volumes was widely used in real-time rendering, and were notably employed in the video game *Doom 3*.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] The particular variation of the technique used in this game has become known as Carmack's Reverse.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] In modern real-time rendering, Shadow mapping techniques and their variations have become more widely used, due to their performance characteristics and compatibility with contemporary rendering pipelines.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] In order to construct a shadow volume, project a ray from the light source through each vertex in the shadow casting object to some point (generally at infinity).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] These projections will together form a volume; any point inside that volume is in shadow, everything outside is lit by the light.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] For a polygonal model, the volume is usually formed by classifying each face in the model as either facing toward the light source or facing away from the light source.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] The set of all edges that connect a toward-face to an away-face form the *silhouette* with respect to the light source.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] The edges forming the silhouette are extruded away from the light to construct the faces of the shadow volume.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] This volume must extend over the range of the entire visible scene; often the dimensions of the shadow volume are extended to infinity to accomplish this (see *optimization* below.) To form a closed volume, the front and back end of this extrusion must be covered.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Depending on the method used for the shadow volume, the front end may be covered by the object itself, and the rear end may sometimes be omitted (see *depth pass* below).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] There is also a problem with the shadow where the faces along the silhouette edge are relatively shallow.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] In this case, the shadow an object casts on itself will be sharp, revealing its polygonal facets, whereas the usual lighting model will have a gradual change in the lighting along the facet.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] This leaves a rough shadow artifact near the silhouette edge which is difficult to correct.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Increasing the polygonal density will minimize the problem, but not eliminate it.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] If the front of the shadow volume is capped, the entire shadow volume may be offset slightly away from the light to remove any shadow self-intersections within the offset distance of the silhouette edge (this solution is more commonly used in shadow mapping).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] After Crow, in 1991 Tim Heidmann showed how to use the stencil buffer to render shadows with shadow volumes quickly enough for use in real time applications.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Render the scene again as if it were completely lit, using the stencil buffer to mask the shadowed areas.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Use additive blending to add this render to the scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] The difference between these three methods occurs in the generation of the mask in the second step.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Some involve two passes, and some only one; some require less precision in the stencil buffer.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Shadow volumes tend to cover large portions of the visible scene, and as a result consume valuable rasterization time (fill time) on 3D graphics hardware.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] This problem is compounded by the complexity of the shadow casting objects, as each object can cast its own shadow volume of any potential size onscreen.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] See *optimization* below for a discussion of techniques used to combat the fill time problem.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Heidmann proposed that if the front surfaces and back surfaces of the shadows were rendered in separate passes, the number of front faces and back faces in front of an object can be counted using the stencil buffer.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] If an object's surface is in shadow, there will be more front facing shadow surfaces between it and the eye than back facing shadow surfaces.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] If their numbers are equal, however, the surface of the object is not in shadow.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Set the stencil operation to increment on depth pass (only count shadows in front of the object).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Render the shadow volumes (because of culling, only their front faces are rendered).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Set the stencil operation to decrement on depth pass.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Render the shadow volumes (only their back faces are rendered).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] According to Euler characteristic, all lit surfaces will correspond to a 0 in the stencil buffer, where the numbers of front and back surfaces of all closed manifolds (shadow volumes) are equal.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] This approach has problems when the eye itself is inside a shadow volume (for example, when the light source moves behind an object).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] From this point of view, the eye sees the back face of this shadow volume before anything else, and this adds a −1 bias to the entire stencil buffer, effectively inverting the shadows.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] This can be remedied by adding a "cap" surface to the front of the shadow volume facing the eye, such as at the front clipping plane.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] There is another situation where the eye may be in the shadow of a volume cast by an object behind the camera, which also has to be capped somehow to prevent a similar problem.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] In most common implementations, because properly capping for depth-pass can be difficult to accomplish, the depth-fail method (see below) may be used for these special situations.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Alternatively one can give the stencil buffer a +1 bias for every shadow volume the camera is inside, though doing the detection can be slow.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] There is another potential problem if the stencil buffer does not have enough bits to accommodate the number of shadows visible between the eye and the object surface, which can potentially cause overflow when there are enough shadow volumes in the scene.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] If saturation arithmetic is used, then the problem can get worse, as some volume calculations can be ignored.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Depth pass testing is also known as **z-pass** testing, as the depth buffer is often referred to as the z-buffer.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Around the year 2000, several people discovered that Heidmann's method can be made to work for all camera positions by reversing the depth.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Instead of counting the shadow surfaces in front of the object's surface, the surfaces behind it can be counted just as easily, with the same end result.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] This solves the problem of the eye being in shadow, since shadow volumes between the eye and the object are not counted, but introduces the condition that the rear end of the shadow volume must be capped, or shadows will end up missing where the volume points backward to infinity.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Set the stencil operation to increment on depth fail (only count shadows behind the object).
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Set the stencil operation to decrement on depth fail.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] The depth fail method has the same considerations regarding the stencil buffer's precision as the depth pass method.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Also, similar to depth pass, it is sometimes referred to as the **z-fail** method.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] William Bilodeau and Michael Songy discovered this technique in October 1998, and presented the technique at Creativity, a Creative Labs developer's conference, in 1999.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Sim Dietrich presented this technique at both GDC in March 1999, and at Creativity in late 1999.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] A few months later, William Bilodeau and Michael Songy filed a US patent application for the technique the same year entitled "Method for rendering shadows using a shadow volume and a stencil buffer".
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] John Carmack of id Software independently discovered the algorithm in 2000 during the development of *Doom 3*. id Software was allowed to use Creative's patent in exchange for the game promoting the company's EAX audio system.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Either of the above types may be approximated with an exclusive-or variation, which does not deal properly with intersecting shadow volumes, but saves one rendering pass (if not fill time), and only requires a 1-bit stencil buffer.
[src:shadow-mapping/shadow-volume] Set the stencil operation to XOR on depth pass (flip on any shadow surface).
